:'''"Bon Language" redirects here. For the language spoken in Cameroon, see [[Bankon language]].'' {{Infobox language |name=Aweer |altname=Boni |states=[[Kenya]] |region=[[Coast Province]], [[North Eastern Province, Kenya|North-Eastern Province]] |ethnicity=[[Aweer people|Aweer]] |speakers=7,600 |date=2009 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] |fam3=[[Lowland East Cushitic languages|Lowland East]] |fam4=[[Rendille–Boni languages|Rendille–Boni]] |iso3=bob |glotto=awee1242 |glottorefname=Aweer |lingua=14-GAF-a }} '''Aweer''' (Aweera), also known as '''Boni''' (Bon, Bonta), is a [[Cushitic language]] of Eastern [[Kenya]]. The [[Aweer people]], known by the arguably derogatory [[Exonym and endonym|exonym]] "Boni," are historically a hunter gatherer people, traditionally subsisting on hunting, gathering, and collecting honey.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Biber|first=Douglas|last2=Heine|first2=Bernd|date=1984|title=The Waata Dialect of Oromo: Grammatical Sketch and Vocabulary|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/413828|journal=Language|volume=60|issue=4|pages=992|doi=10.2307/413828|issn=0097-8507|via=}}</ref> Their ancestral lands range along the Kenyan coast from the [[Lamu County|Lamu]] and [[Ijara District|Ijara]] Districts into Southern [[Somalia|Somalia's]] [[Badhadhe District|Badaade District]].<ref>A.H.J. Prins. 1960 Notes on the Boni, a Tribe of Hunters in Northern Kenya. ''Bulletin of the International Committee on Urgent Anthropological and Ethnological Research.'' Vol. 1 (3): 25-27; 1963 The Didemic Diarchic Boni. ''The Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute.'' Vol. 93 (2): 174-85.</ref>
According to ''[[Ethnologue]]'', there are around 8,000 speakers of Aweer. Aweer has similarities with the [[Garre language]],<ref>Raymond G. Gordon Jr., ed. 2005. ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World''. 15th edition. Dallas: Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref><ref name="Ethngex">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=gex Ethnologue - Garre language]</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=Mauro|last=Tosco|year=1994|title=The Historical Reconstruction of a Southern Somali Dialect: Proto-Karre-Boni|journal=Sprache und Geschichte in Afrika|volume=15|pages=153–209|url=https://www.academia.edu/4248545/The_historical_reconstruction_of_a_Southern_Somali_dialect_Proto-Karre-Boni}}</ref> however, its speakers are ethnically distinct from Garre speakers.<ref name="Ethnbob">[http://archive.ethnologue.com/16/show_language.asp?code=bob Ethnologue - Aweer language]</ref>
Evidence suggests that the Aweer are remnants of the early hunter-gatherer inhabitants of Eastern Africa. According to linguistic, anthropological and other data, these groups later came under the influence of [[Lowland East Cushitic languages|Eastern]] and [[South Cushitic languages|Southern Cushitic]] peoples and adopted [[Afroasiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic languages]].<ref name="Aminmoll">{{cite book|last=Mohamed Amin|first=Peter Moll|title=Portraits of Africa|year=1983|publisher=Harvill Press|isbn=0002726394|pages=16}}</ref>
